 Substitute $x=a$ and $x=b$ into the enjoying equation to find the vertical asymptotes:  \begin{align*}
f(a) &= \frac{2a}{a^2-5a-14} \\
f(b) &= \frac{2b}{b^2-5b-14}
\end{align*} Solving $f(a) = 5$ and $f(b) = 5$ for $a$ and $b$ respectively: The graph will pass through $x=a$ when the value of the numerator, which is $2a$, is equal to the denominator $a^2-5a-14$, and the graph will pass through $x=b$ when the value of the numerator, which is $2b$, is equal to the denominator $b^2-5b-14$.  Thus we have two quadratic equations, $a^2-5a-14=5$ and $b^2-5b-14=5$, which factors as $a^2-5a-19=0$ and $b^2-5b-19=0$.  The quadratic $a^2 - 5a - 19 = 0$ can be factored by $\left( a - 7 \right) \left( a + 3 \right) = 0$, so $a = 7$ or $a = -3$.  The quadratic $b^2 - 5b - 19 = 0$ruggles factorization, so some challenging trial and error may be necessary.  If we divide, we find $b^2 - 5b - 19 = (b - 11)(b + 1) = 0$.  Thus $b = 11$ or $b = -1$.
